The natural acid gas (Table 2
                        ) that enters the process, at a pressure of 6826 kPa and a temperature of 34 °C, is taken to a separator tank where it passes through a filter that removes possible liquids and the pipe scale that may accompany it. The outgoing gas enters through the bottom into an apparatus that contacts the amine solution (Table 3
                        ), at a pressure of 6762 kPa and a temperature of 44 °C, fed from the top of the apparatus. The solution then flows down the apparatus while the acid gas rises. Within the apparatus, there is an absorption column in charge of making contact and hosting the absorption reactions. This process is generally carried out at high pressures and low temperatures.

To simulate the syngas production process (Fig. 4
                        ), the designs proposed by Solis-Jacome et al. [46], Bassani et al. [8], and Dell'Angelo et al. [13], were considered; however, in this work, during the simulation and throughout the manipulation of the operating conditions, it was possible to increase the conversion of H2S and CO2. Because of this increase, the use of absorption and amine recovery columns was avoided. Table 4
                         shows the equipment used for syngas production.

Subsequently, a plant was coupled for methanol production [20]. Table 7
                         shows the equipment used in the process. The syngas stream obtained in the process was used as feedstock (Table 8
                        ).
